The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Toyota bets on second plant
                                                                                                               Toyota bets on second plant
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Toyota Kirloskar Motors managing director Hiroshi Nakagawa in Mumbai on Tuesday. (AFP)                                  
	Mumbai, June 9: Toyota will start production at its second plant in India from the end of 2010. The plant will make a new compact car and have capacity to roll out 70,000 units a year.         
	Toyota Kirloskar Motor Pvt Ltd (TKM), the Indian venture between Japans Toyota Motor Corp and the Kirloskar group, will invest Rs 3,000 crore in the unit that will come up in Karnataka. Officials said the production at the new plant could be quickly ramped to 100,000 units.        
	The compact car will roll out of a new platform. It will mainly be targeted at the local market though a part of the production will be exported.        
	Toyota today launched the Land Cruiser here. The premium SUV will compete against the Audi Q7.        
	TKM managing director Hiroshi Nakagawa unveiled the eighth generation Land Cruiser, which would be available in two options. One will have nine speakers and the other will have an advanced speaker system with a moon roof. These options will be available at Rs 81.64 lakh and Rs 83.1 lakh (ex-showroom Thane), respectively.        
	Nakagawa said TKM hoped to sell around 50,000 units this year. It sold 51,800 vehicles last year. Its current plant in Karnataka has capacity to make 60,000 units of the Corolla Altis and the Innova. It imports the Camry and the Prado as CBUs.                                                                                                                                        
